name: YANG
bio: [('Beginning', "He took up the sport in 1998 in Hangzhou, People's Republic of China. (2012.sina.com.cn, 30 Jul 2012)"), ('Reason', "His potential was recognized by a teacher at Jinglun Sports School in Hangzhou, People's Republic of China. (2012.sina.com.cn, 30 Jul 2012)"), ('Debut', '2007 for China, World Championships in Melbourne, Australia (sports.sina.com.hk, 02 Mar 2007)'), ('Coach', 'Zhu Zhigen [club], CHN (sports.hangzhou.com.cn, 04 Jun 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win multiple gold medals at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (finance.sina.com.cn, 17 May 2017)'), ('Awards', 'In 2017 he was presented with a prize for his "Outstanding Contribution for Swimming Popularity in China" by the International Swimming Federation [FINA]. (fina.org, 02 Dec 2017)He was named the 2016 Male Athlete of Year by the sport bureau of Zhejiang province. (sports.sina.com.cn, 2017)In 2013 and 2015 he was named Best Male Swimmer at the world championships. (olympictalk.nbcsports.com, 09 Aug 2015; sports.sina.com.cn, 05 Aug 2013)In 2011 and 2012 he was named Best Male Athlete at the China Central Television [CCTV] Sports Personality of the Year awards. (hinews.cn, 05 Feb 2013; sports.qq.com, 15 Jan 2012)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Chinese swimmer to win an Olympic gold medal when he placed first in the 400m freestyle at the 2012 Games in London. (nytimes.com, 28 Jul 2012)SANCTIONHe tested positive for the prohibited substance trimetazidine at the 2014 National Championships in Hangzhou, People's Republic of China. He was banned from the sport for three months by the China Anti-Doping Agency [CHINADA]. Sun claimed he had been taking medication containing trimetazidine to treat a heart condition since 2008 and was unaware it had been added to the World Anti-Doping Agency [WADA] banned list in 2014. (sports.163.com, 25 Nov 2014) "), ('Hero', 'Chinese swimmer Zhang Lin. (sports.people.com.cn, 30 Jul 2012)'), ('Relatives', "His father played basketball for Anhui Tigong, and his mother competed in volleyball for Zhejiang in the People's Republic of China. (sports.163.com, 18 Sep 2012; sports.cn.yahoo.com, 11 Sep 2012; sports.people.com.cn, 30 Jul 2012)"), ('Nickname', 'The Underwater Meteor (dzxw.net, 29 Jul 2012)'), ('Injuries', 'He was affected by a high fever during the 1500m heats at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro, and he failed to progress through to the next round. (ONS, 13 Aug 2016)He broke the fifth metatarsal bone in his right foot during a training session in Australia in January 2016. He returned to training in March 2016. (gzdaily.dayoo.com, 30 Jan 2016)He withdrew from the final of the 1500m freestyle at the 2015 World Championships in Kazan, Russian Federation, due to what he described as heart problems. (olympictalk.nbcsports.com, 09 Aug 2015)He had foot surgery for a toenail infection in February 2014. (swimvortex.com, 07 Mar 2014; cntv.cn, 21 Mar 2014)'), ('Education', 'Sport Studies - Zhejiang University, Hangzhou, CHN'), ('Languages', 'Mandarin'), ('Hobbies', 'Listening to music. name: JOSEPH ISAAC
bio: [('Beginning', 'He learned to swim at age four. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'His talent was spotted at an early age and he was given the opportunity of attending the private Bolles School swimming institution in Jacksonville, FL, United States of America. "My parents wanted me to [learn to swim], because Singapore is surrounded by water. I enjoyed swimming so much. When they put me under the water I wasn\'t afraid, unlike other kids. I just used to giggle and found I really liked being in the water." (foxsports asia.com, 30 Mar 2016; prischew.com, 19 Nov 2013)'), ('Debut', '2011 for Singapore (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Stephan Widmer [national], AUS; Gary Tan [national], SGP (swimming.org.sg, 14 Jun 2018; swimmingworldmagazine.com, 18 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To break the world record in the 100m butterfly. (swimswam.com, 15 Jun 2017)'), ('Awards', "In 2014 and 2016 he was named The Straits Times Athlete of the Year in Singapore. (swimswam.com, 20 Feb 2017, 05 Mar 2015)He was voted the 2015 Men's Swimmer of the Year by the Big 12 Conference in the United States of America. (texassports.com, 19 Apr 2016)He was named the 2014 Swimmer of the Year by the Singapore Swimming Association [SSA]. (todayonline.com, 26 Apr 2015) He was named the 2012 Sportsman of the Year at the Singapore Sports Awards. At age 16, he was the youngest person to have won the award. (yahoo.com, 30 May 2012)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first athlete from Singapore to win a gold medal at the Olympic Games when he triumphed in the 100m butterfly at the 2016 Games in Rio de Janeiro. He beat his idol Michael Phelps to claim the title. (ONS, 14 Aug 2016)RIO BLUESHe admitted that he got distracted from the sport in the months after winning gold in the 100m butterfly at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. "Having so much attention, and on such a large scale, can definitely be overwhelming, and you can definitely lose yourself. That was where I was from August to December [in 2016]. Now, I tell myself, \'Keep doing well, accomplish what you want to do. All the opportunities will come and you can enjoy them when you\'re done with swimming\'." (swimswam.com, 15 Jun 2017)DEFERRED MILITARY TIMEIn October 2013 the Singapore government agreed he could delay his national service until August 2016, which would allow him to focus on training ahead of the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. In August 2016 it was announced his deferment had been extended until after the 2020 Games in Tokyo. "I\'m doing this because I love my country. I want to bring pride and glory to my country. If you ask me if swimming itself is a form of national service, I couldn\'t answer that question. It\'s not up to me. My job is to swim." (straitstimes.com, 15 Aug 2016; yahoo.com, 02 Dec 2013; straitstimes.com, 21 Oct 2013) '), ('Hero', 'US swimmer Michael Phelps. (todayonline.com, 04 Jun 2016)'), ('Influence', 'His parents. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Relatives', 'His uncle Lloyd Valberg represented Singapore in athletics at the 1948 Olympic Games in London. (SportsDeskOnline, 28 Apr 2015; straitstimes.com, 24 Sep 2014)'), ('Nickname', 'Jo (swimswam.com, 29 Mar 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'He competed at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, despite suffering from nerve damage in his right shoulder. (asiaone.com, 24 Sep 2014)He suffered a sprained ankle in 2012. name: YOSHIAKI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began riding at about age 10. (atozinba.com, 08 Jun 2017)'), ('Reason', 'He initially got involved in equestrian sport as a hobby. "At about age 14, I started riding every day and enjoying showjumping competitions. My first time eventing was for a university competition, and we had no choice but to do all three disciplines." (JEF, 20 Apr 2017; Twitter profile, 06 Jul 2017; atozinba.com, 08 Jun 2017) '), ('Hero', 'Japanese showjumper Takeichi Nishi. (Athlete, 23 Jun 2012)'), ('Influence', 'Coach Dirk Schrade (Athlete, 23 Jun 2012)'), ('Relatives', 'His aunt Mieko Fujimori was a Japanese champion figure skater. name: MOHD AZIZULHASNI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began cycling at age 10 in his hometown of Dungun, Malaysia. (puncakbikers.blogspot.com, 08 Aug 2012)'), ('Reason', 'He followed his brother to a cycling club, and used the bike given to him by his father as a reward for good exam results. "At 15 years old, I was determined to pursue cycling and left for Bukit Jalil Sports School. My parents were not too happy with my decision to become a sportsman because they wanted me to become a doctor but I was adamant with my dream of becoming a national champion in track cycling." (eurosport.yahoo.com, 07 Jun 2012; thestar.com.my, 26 Jun 2012; yayasansimedarby.com, 21 Mar 2016)'), ('Debut', '2007 (Athlete, 07 Mar 2012)'), ('Coach', 'John Beasley [national], AUS (thestar.com.my, 06 Jun 2018)'), ('Awards', "He received the 2017 Sportswriters Association of Malaysia Best Athlete Award. He won the same award in 2009. (thestar.com.my, 02 Mar 2018)In 2015 he received the Full Blue Award for sporting achievements from Victoria University, making him the first non-Australian to be given the award. (yayasansimedarby.com, 08 Mar 2016)He was named Terengganu Sportsman of the Year in 2010, 2011 and 2012. (astroawani.com, 25 Dec 2012)He was Malaysia's flag bearer at the opening ceremony of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (mncf.org.my, 27 Jul 2012; thepocketrocketman.blogspot.com, 01 May 2013)He was named Malaysian Sportsman of the Year in 2009 and 2010. (mncf.org.my, 27 Jul 2012; Facebook page, 06 Mar 2016)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Malaysian cyclist to win a medal at the Olympic Games when he finished third in the keirin at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (cyclingnews.com, 17 Aug 2016; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018) '), ('Influence', 'His wife and his family. (top10malaysia.com, 27 Jul 2012; Instagram profile, 03 Mar 2016)'), ('Nickname', 'Pocket Rocket Man, Jijoe (thepocketrocketman.blogspot.com, 01 May 2013; Facebook page, 06 Mar 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'A viral infection in his lungs forced him to withdraw from the individual sprint event at the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia. He did compete in the keirin event at the Games. (nst.com.my, 05 Apr 2018)He withdrew from the 2016 World Championships in London, England, after falling ill due to a flu virus and tearing his thigh muscle in an accident during his training. (yayasansimedarby.com, 08 Mar 2016)In 2011 he dislocated his knee during an event in Indonesia. (uk.eurosport.yahoo.com, 07 Jun 2012)In February 2011 at the World Cup event in Manchester, England, his left calf was impaled by a shard of wood during a crash. He finished the race in third place before having the shard removed in hospital. The injury caused him to miss the world championships in Apeldoorn, Netherlands, the following month. (dailymail.co.uk, 23 Feb 2011; thestar.com.my, 26 Jun 2012; my.sports.yahoo.com, 19 Jun 2013)'), ('Education', 'Victoria University, Melbourne, VIC, AUS'), ('Languages', 'English, Malay'), name: SANGHOON
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport in grade seven at Mokcheon Middle School in Cheonan, Republic of Korea. (sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016; view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017)'), ('Reason', 'He was influenced by his father. He joined the cycling team because he "wanted to enjoy cycling as a supplement to a diet". (news.joins.com, 22 Sep 2014; sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Jang Yoon-Ho [club], KOR; Um In-Young [national], KOR; Jang Sun-Jae [national], KOR (newsmaker.or.kr, 14 Apr 2018; sports.news.naver.com, 21 Jun 2018; cycling.or.kr, 04 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017)'), ('Awards', 'In 2017, he was presented with a Cycling Grand Award by the Korea Cycling Federation. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 31 Jan 2018)In 2015, he was named Cyclist of the Year by the Korea Cycling Federation. (moneyweek.co.kr, 02 Feb 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralAPOLOGYBritish cyclist Mark Cavendish called him to apologise after a crash between the two during the omnium final at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. "He said sorry and told me that it was his fault for changing direction suddenly. He also sent a text message expressing his hope that I recover soon, and said that he wants to compete with me again. It was also my fault that I couldn\'t predict his movement. This kind of fall often happens in cycling. I\'m fine now." (sports-g.com, 01 Sep 2016)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first male Republic of Korea cyclist to win a gold medal at the Junior World Track Championships when he claimed a victory in the individual pursuit at the 2011 Worlds in Moscow, Russian Federation. (cyclingweekly.com, 18 Aug 2011; news.donga.com, 17 May 2016, SportsDeskOnline 31 Jul 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Coach Cho Ho-Sung. (news.donga.com, 17 May 2016)'), ('Influence', 'Cycling coach Cho Ho-Sung who convinced him to switch from the omnium to the individual pursuit. (stnsports.co.kr, 03 Jan 2016)'), ('Relatives', "His father Park Myung-Sun won a bronze medal for the Republic of Korea in the cycling road team event at the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing, People's Republic of China. He later became a cycling coach. (view.asiae.co.kr, 19 Jan 2017; news.joins.com, 22 Sep 2014)"), ('Injuries', 'He was carried off the velodrome on a stretcher during the omnium final at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro after a heavy crash with British cyclist Mark Cavendish. He escaped the incident with only bruises and Cavendish, the silver medallist in the event, accepted responsibility for the crash. name: RAMZY HAMAD
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport at age 10 in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Reason', 'He discovered his love for equestrian after first jumping with one of his father\'s Arabian horses. "My father bought us eight horses to keep on the farm. My brothers and I started riding, especially my eldest brother who had a bit more experience with horses." (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012; horsetimesegypt.com, 22 Aug 2011)'), ('Debut', '1990 for Saudi Arabia, in Yokohama, Japan (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTIn 2012 he was a member of the team that won Saudi Arabia\'s first team medal in equestrian at the Olympic Games when they claimed bronze in jumping in London. (ashgabat2017.com, 20 Sep 2017; saudiequestrian.com, 19 Oct 2013)BUSINESSMANHe has been a partner in one of Saudi Arabia\'s leading contracting companies. He has also run an equestrian business called Elite Horses in Saudi Arabia that offers training for horses and riders, tack and feed shops, an equine transportation company and a stable construction and management business. "I want to be able to provide the Arab region with the same quality of equestrian services that other countries offer today. After all, we come from a part of the world where horses are a part of our identity and are revered as symbols of freedom, strength and power." (cavalor.com, 20 Mar 2015; elitehorses.com, 2011)OTHER ACTIVITIESHe has served as president of the International Equestrian Federation [FEI] Arab Riders club committee. He has also worked as trainer of the Saudi young riders jumping team. (elitehorses.com, 2011) '), ('Hero', 'His mother. (Athlete, 04 Jul 2012)'), ('Influence', 'His father. name: DATTU BABAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up rowing in 2012 in Khadki, India. (indiatimes.com, 26 Apr 2016)'), ('Reason', 'He was introduced to rowing after joining the army despite not being able to swim. "I was scared of drowning, really scared. The guy who does not know how to swim, he is going to row a boat. I used to be so nervous. Initially my boat turned many times and I had to get across to the bank of the river along with my boat and then start again." (news18.com, 30 Apr 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Ismail Baig [national], IND; Nicolae Gioga [national], ROU (thehindu.com, 26 Jun 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (deccanchronicle.com, 24 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', 'In 2018 he received the Shiv Chhatrapati State Sports Award from the Government of Maharashtra in India. (hindustantimes.com, 19 Feb 2018)He was named the 2016 Rower of the Year at the Times of India Sports Awards ceremony in Mumbai, India. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 20 Mar 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralOTHER STUDIESHe has also studied at the Arts, Commerce and Science College in Lasalgaon, India. (Facebook profile, 11 Jun 2018)OCCUPATIONHe joined the Indian Army under a sports quota programme that allows him to train and compete internationally. (newindianexpress.com, 14 Mar 2018)RIO MOTIVATIONHe qualified for the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro after finishing second in the single sculls at the 2016 Asia and Oceania Olympic qualification regatta in Chungju, Republic of Korea. This was despite his mother being in an intensive care unit with a brain injury. "In my heart of hearts I thought qualification for Rio is the best gift I could have given her and that spurred me to achieve my objective." (thehindu.com, 04 May 2016; news18.com, 30 Apr 2016)EARLY DAYSHe initially found it difficult to adjust to rowing after coming from a village where water was in short supply. "I didn\'t get the logic [of rowing]. The only thing I could think of was to take some water from the [training] centre back home. Water was very scarce in our village. We didn\'t even have water to drink. Trust me, it\'s worth more than gold. How could we imagine it could be used for sport as well?" (indiatimes.com, 26 Apr 2016) '), ('Education', 'University of Pune, India'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games5Double Sculls2014Incheon, KOR6:37.02Olympic Games13Single Sculls2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA6:54.96Asian Championships2Single Sculls2015Beijing, CHN7:18.41')]

(timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Amrish Kumar [personal], IND (scroll.in, 28 Aug 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralTOUGH TIMESHe came close to quitting the sport in 2016 after his employer, Oil and Natural Gas Corporation of India [ONGC], decided to not renew his contract. He found it difficult to cover his training costs as his father was the only member of his family that was earning a salary. However, he then met coach Amrish Kumar, who motivated him to persevere. "I was on stipend for three years and then they told me I wasn\'t going to be made permanent. I was almost ready to quit the sport. I was 27 and still taking support from my parents." (scroll.in, 28 Aug 2018; espn.in, 27 Aug 2018) '), ('Relatives', 'His father Randhir Singh Chahal competed in shot put at state level in India. name: Ehsan
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up discus at age 16. (iaaf.org, 05 Jun 2008)'), ('Reason', 'He took aim at goal in a school handball match and threw the ball with such power it broke the goalpost. His surprised sports teacher told him he had to take part in a throwing sport. "I have always loved throwing ever since I was a child. Even when we went to the Caspian Sea, I threw rocks into the sea." (thestar.com.my, 27 Jul 2008)'), ('Coach', 'Mac Wilkins [personal], USA (usatf.org, 09 May 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (tasnimnews.com, 12 Aug 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHe became the first Iranian to win a medal in athletics at the Olympic Games, when he took silver in discus at the 2012 Games in London. He was also the first Iranian to win a medal at the world championships, following his bronze medal in discus at the 2011 edition in Daegu, Republic of Korea. (presstv.ir, 07 Aug 2012; parsherald.com, 20 Apr 2013; SportsDeskOnline, 16 May 2018)EARLY YEARSHe quit the sport in his youth after not being selected for the national school championships in Iran. He returned to the sport four years later when a coach noticed his physical attributes at an athletics competition he attended as a spectator. "I remember as if it were now when a coach came to me, asked me to stand up and measured my height and arm span, keeping silent. Then he said that I can be a good discus thrower and invited me to his group." (iaaf.org, 17 Jul 2012) '), ('Injuries', 'His performance was hindered by injury at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. He underwent three surgeries on his left knee and heel following the Games and was unable to walk for three months. (tasnimnews.com, 12 Aug 2016; sportstarlive.com, 07 Jul 2017)'), ('Languages', 'English, Farsi, Russian'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games1Discus Throw2014Incheon, KOR65.111Discus Throw2010Guangzhou, CHN67.991Discus Throw2006Doha, QAT63.79Olympic Games2Discus Throw2012London, GBR68.18QualificationDiscus Throw2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA60.15QualificationDiscus Throw2008Beijing, CHN61.34World Championships3Discus Throw2011Daegu, KOR66.087Discus Throw2007Osaka, JPN64.53QualificationDiscus Throw2017London, GBR63.03QualificationDiscus Throw2015Beijing, CHN60.39Diamond League2Discus Throw2018Oslo, NOR67.553Discus Throw2018Stockholm, SWE67.683Discus Throw2018Rome, ITA65.936Discus Throw2018Paris Saint-Denis, FRA64.366Discus Throw2015Oslo, NOR60.466Discus Throw2015Eugene, OR, USA61.67World Challenge3Discus Throw2016Madrid, ESP63.105Discus Throw2018Ostrava, CZE64.45Asian Championships1Discus Throw2017Bhubaneswar, IND64.541Discus Throw2011Kobe, JPN62.271Discus Throw2009Guangzhou, CHN64.831Discus Throw2007Amman, JOR65.38NMDiscus Throw2015Wuhan, CHNNM')]

name: NAN
bio: [('Beginning', "He took up the sport at age nine in Beijing, People's Republic of China. (badmintoncn.com, 20 Jul 2014)"), ('Reason', 'His family hoped playing badminton could improve his physical fitness. "I got sick often when I was a child, so my parents decided to send me to play sport. I preferred football, but my family thought the risk of getting hurt was high if I played football. name: Abbas
bio: [('Additional Information', 'GeneralNIGERIA TO BAHRAINHe was born in Kano, Nigeria, and chose to compete for Bahrain at age 16. He later disclosed that it was easy turning to Bahrain because of the poor treatment he had received from the Athletics Federation of Nigeria [AFN]. "I never thought of running for another country. I wanted to represent my country, Nigeria, but a lot of things are happening in Nigeria and in the way the Nigerian federation treat athletes. I once ran in a relay and we had silver. When we came back, nobody called us to even thank us. I ran 47 seconds [in the 400m] when I was 15 but nobody encouraged me. Nobody said, \'Let\'s take care of this guy, next time he will do better.\'" (Saddam Muhammad Facebook page, 15 Apr 2016; ogtv.com.ng. 06 Sep 2015)NATIONAL FIRSTSBy finishing second in the 400m semifinal at the 2013 World Youth Championships in Donetsk, Ukraine, he became the first athlete from Bahrain to qualify for a final in that distance at a youth or senior world championship. He was also the first Bahraini athlete to win a medal in a sprint event at the World Junior Championships, following his bronze medal in the 400m at the 2014 edition in Eugene, OR, United States of America. (gulf-daily-news.com, 12 Jul 2013; gulf-daily-news.com, 26 Jul 2014; SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jul 2018) '), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games2400m2014Incheon, KOR45.62Heats200m2014Incheon, KORDNSOlympic GamesRound 1400m2016Rio de Janeiro, BRADSQWorld ChampionshipsHeats400m2015Beijing, CHN45.64World Challenge10400m2018Madrid, ESP45.77Asian Championships4400m2015Wuhan, CHN46.15')]

name: ROHAN MANCHANDA
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up tennis at age 11, and he began taking it seriously at age 19. (atpworldtour.com, 27 Jun 2016)'), ('Reason', '"Though I played cricket, hockey and football at school, individual sport fascinated me more, because I wanted to be in control of my game." (kodaguconnect.com, 19 Nov 2012)'), ('Debut', 'Turned professional in 2003'), ('Coach', 'Zeeshan Ali [national] (deccanherald.com, 04 Jun 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 29 Jul 2018)'), ('Awards', 'He received the Sports Icon of the Year award at the 2018 Indian Oil Sports Conclave. (tennisworldusa.org, 10 Jun 2018)He received the Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP] Arthur Ashe Humanitarian of the Year award in 2010. (atpworldtour.com, 27 Jun 2016)He was awarded the Eklavya award by the Government of Karnataka in India in 2005 for his achievements in the field of tennis. (thenews.com.pk, 10 May 2012)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralOCCUPATIONHe joined the Indian Oil Corporation under a sports quota programme that allows him to train and compete internationally. (tennisworldusa.org, 10 Jun 2018)BUSINESS VENTURESIn July 2018 he launched Cardio Workout, a fitness programme that combines a range of innovative tennis games and cardiovascular exercises. In January 2018 he also launched his coffee brand Rohan Bopanna's Master Blend in collaboration with coffee chain The Flying Squirrel. (cnbctv18.com, 30 Jul 2018; yourstory.com, 30 Jan 2018)TENNIS ACADEMYHe runs the Rohan Bopanna Tennis Academy in Bengaluru, India, which was started in March 2016 to promote tennis and offer coaching to young players. (rohanbopannatennis.com, 01 Apr 2018)COMMUNITY WORKAlong with Pakistani tennis player Aisam-Ul-Haq Qureshi he created the 'Stop War Start Tennis' campaign, to help victims of landmines and other weapons of war in past and present conflict zones. He has also funded a school for children with impairments in his hometown of Coorg, India and contributed to the Coorg Institute of Dental Sciences to help provide low cost dental treatment to the poor. name: YOSHITAKU
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began the sport at age four. (fatbmx.com, 22 Jan 2015)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete in both track cycling and BMX at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (uci.ch, 10 Apr 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralTOKYO DREAMHe has ambitions to compete in both track cycling and BMX at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. "I started track cycling when I was based at the UCI World Cycling Centre. We trained sometimes on the velodrome. I liked it and I thought I might have the potential to be a starter for the team sprint. It\'s not easy racing all year round but the playing fields are different. The people are different, the bike is different. It\'s good for me to change sometimes." (uci.ch, 10 Apr 2017; cyclingnews.com, 12 Apr 2017)MOVE ABROADHe moved from Japan to Switzerland in 2012 to train under coach Thomas Allier at the UCI World Cycling Centre in Aigle, Switzerland. In 2016 he left Switzerland and moved to California, United States of America. (fatbmx.com, 22 Jan 2015; 15.ie, 15 Mar 2016; uci.ch, 10 Apr 2017; Instagram profile, 28 Jul 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Latvian BMX rider Maris Strombergs. name: Wai Hung
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up gymnastics at age six. (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)'), ('Reason', 'He was inspired to take up the sport after watching gymnastics on television. (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)'), ('Debut', '2004 for Hong Kong, China (FIG, 08 Jan 2010)'), ('Coach', 'Sergiy Agafontsev [national], UKR (singpao.com.hk, 01 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (hk01.com, 04 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning gold in men's vault at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (Facebook page, 17 Jul 2017; scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)"), ('Awards', 'In 2014 and 2015 he was named Gymnastics Sports Star of the Year by the Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, China. (scmp.com, 21 Mar 2016; sportstar2017.hkolympic.org, 01 Jan 2016)He was a torchbearer as the relay made its way through Hong Kong, China ahead of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (Facebook page, 05 Jun 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralLONDON DISAPPOINTMENTHe was unable to progress beyond the first round of the men\'s vault competition at the 2012 Olympic Games in London. He was so disappointed that he considered quitting the sport, but winning gold at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, went some way towards helping him erase the memory. "I wanted to die right there - all my hard work and effort over so many years disappeared in a flash. I have been haunted by that terrible moment for a long time. At one time, I even wanted to quit the sport. Even before the Incheon Games, I was still thinking about it. Hopefully, this success can help me forget it." (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first male gymnast to represent Hong Kong, China at an Olympic Games when he competed at the 2012 Games in London. "It\'s like a dream come true. I started training at the age of seven and going to the Olympic Games has always been my biggest ambition." (SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jul 2017; scmp.com, 12 Jan 2012) '), ('Hero', 'Chinese gymnast Zou Kai. (sportsroad.hk, 06 Aug 2014)'), ('Nickname', 'Stone (Facebook page, 05 Jun 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'He sustained ligament damage to his right shoulder while competing at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. bio: [('Beginning', "He began riding at age six on his family's farm. He took up showjumping at age 17. (timeoutdoha.com, 30 Nov 2014)"), ('Reason', 'He was encouraged to try riding by his cousins. He took up judo in Japan, and continued the sport at the University of Tsukuba. In 2013 he won gold medals in the individual and team events at the All Japan Student Judo Tournament, and received an offer to represent Japan in international competition from the All Japan Judo Federation. However, he wanted to compete for his homeland, so he transferred to Yong In University in 2014 and was selected in the Republic of Korea national team the same year. (sportsseoul.com, 07 Jan 2016; yonhapnews.co.kr, 06 Jul 2015; news.donga.com, 29 Dec 2014) '), ('Influence', 'Korean judoka Ahn Byung-Keun. name: RAJAT
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up archery in 2007 in Jaipur, India. (indianwomenblog.org, 19 Sep 2016)'), ('Reason', '"Initially my inclination towards sports was majorly because I could bunk classes, and even my family didn\'t mind my low scores in academics as they knew I was focusing on my game. I remember how I chose archery. My elder brother had given me a few options, but I couldn\'t make up my mind. So, I just went to Sawai Mansingh Stadium with a friend on his bike. We entered from the Tonk Road side, and the first ground I saw was for archery so I took it as a God\'s sign." (indianwomenblog.org, 19 Sep 2016)'), ('Debut', '2011 for India (indianexpress.com, 05 Aug 2015)'), ('Coach', 'Jiwanjot Singh Teja [national], IND; Dhaneshwar Maida [national], IND (sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in, 11 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (patrika.com, 01 Nov 2017)'), ('Awards', "In 2016 he received the Arjuna Award from the Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports in India. (Facebook page, 27 Apr 2018; dnaindia.com, 22 Aug 2016)He received the World Archery Federation's Purple and Gold Target awards in 2013. (starlive24.in, 20 Dec 2013)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSAfter winning gold in the men\'s team compound event at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, he and teammates Abhishek Verma and Sandeep Kumar became the first Indian archers to win a gold medal at the Asian Games. He also became the first Indian archer to win an individual medal at the world championships, following his silver medal in the men\'s compound event at the 2015 edition in Copenhagen, Denmark. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 27 Sep 2014; indianwomenblog.org, 19 Sep 2016; indianexpress.com, 05 Aug 2015; SportsDeskOnline, 27 Jun 2018)EARLY DAYSAs a child his mother Nirmala Chauhan raised two lakh of Indian rupees by selling gold ornaments to buy him an imported archery kit from the United States of America. "Gold bangles are nothing before my son\'s dream and achievements. All I want is him to do his country proud," she said. (Youtube.com, 25 Feb 2012; kridangan.com, 08 Oct 2013) '), ('Influence', 'His parents. name: SAEID
bio: [('Coach', 'Mohammad Hossein Barkhah [national], IRI (insidethegames.biz, 07 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (reuters.com, 06 Dec 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSANCTIONSIn 2009 he tested positive for the prohibited substance metandienone during an out-of-competition test. He had also tested positive for clenbuterol earlier in his career, resulting in a two-year suspension between 2006 and 2008, which meant he was banned from the sport for life by the International Weightlifting Federation [IWF]. In 2011 the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS] reduced the ban to 12 years, after accepting his first offence had been the result of a coach doping Iranian weightlifters without their knowledge. Ali Hosseini then made a second successful appeal and his suspension was cut to eight years. He became eligible to return to competition in October 2017. (mojnews.com, 23 Oct 2017; iwf.net, 01 Oct 2017; espn.co.uk, 26 Oct 2011) '), ('Hero', 'US sprinter Justin Gatlin. (insidethegames.biz, 06 Dec 2017)'), ('Injuries', 'He was affected by a knee injury ahead of the 2017 World Championships. name: Dilshod
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took part in his first competition at age 14. (iaaf.org, 29 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'He initially played basketball and tennis, before switching to athletics. (tjk.rus4all.ru, 25 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Vladimir Mashko [personal], CZE (rus.ozodi.org, 02 Aug 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning gold in the hammer throw at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (rus.ozodi.org, 21 Aug 2016)'), ('Awards', "In 2017 the Asian Athletics Association named him the Best Track and Field Athlete of Asia. (news.tj, 06 Jul 2017)In 2015 and 2016 he received the Sharaf Orders [Orders of Glory, second and first grades] in Tajikistan. (tojnews.org, 28 Aug 2015; avesta.tj, 27 Aug 2016)He was named Athlete of the Year by the National Association of Sports Journalists in Tajikistan for four consecutive years between 2013 and 2016. (rus.ozodi.org, 09 Feb 2016; news.tj, 23 Dec 2013; 06 Feb 2015; 20 Dec 2016)He was Tajikistan's flag bearer during the opening ceremonies of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing and the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (xinhuanet.com, 08 Aug 2008; tajikistantimes.com, 18 Jul 2016)In December 2016 he was named an honorary citizen of the capital city of Dushanbe in Tajikistan. (news.tj, 16 Dec 2016)He has received the title of Honoured Master of Sport in Tajikistan. (olympic.tj, 23 Jul 2016)"), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHe became the first Tajikistani athlete to win a gold medal in any sport at the Olympic Games when he was victorious in the hammer throw at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. He also became the first Tajikistani athlete to win a gold medal in any sport at the Asian Games, following his victory in the hammer throw at the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. (iaaf.org, 29 Aug 2016; china.org.cn, 09 Dec 2006)OTHER ACTIVITIESDuring his career he has served as deputy chairman of the Committee for Youth, Sports and Tourism of the Government of Tajikistan and as chairman of Tajikistan's Athletics Federation. (youth.tj, 2018; asiaplus.tj, 18 May 2017)FURTHER STUDIESIn 2006 he graduated from the Tajik State University of Commerce in Dushanbe, Tajikistan. (olympic.tj, 23 Jul 2016) "), ('Hero', 'His father. name: SONCHAT
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up tennis at age seven in Bangkok, Thailand. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', 'His father introduced him to the sport. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Debut', 'Turned professional in 2004'), ('Coach', 'Veerapat Phokrakul [national], THA; Braen Aneiros, PAN (sportringside.com, 28 May 2018; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning the men's doubles title at the 2007 Thailand Open and 2008 Chennai Open. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDOMINANT FORCEHe and his brother Sanchai are a dominant force in the doubles Challenger circuit, the second tier of the Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP]. Entering the 2018 season they had won a record 46 doubles tournaments since they began playing together in 2004. As a result they have been referred to as \'the Bryans of the ATP Challengers\' in reference to US twins Bob and Mike Bryan, who are the most successful duo in the ATP\'s top tier. "They are our idols. To be honest, they are incomparable. They are far, far in front of us as players," said Sanchai. The Thai twins say they do not mind the comparison, but would rather be known for their own achievements. "We want to be known as Ratiwatanas - King of the Challengers," Sanchai said. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; sportstarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTHe and his twin brother Sanchai became the first Thai tennis players to win an Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP] doubles event when they won the 2007 Thailand Open in Bangkok, Thailand. In 2016 they became the first Thai male doubles team to compete at an Olympic Games. (nationmultimedia.com, 03 Oct 2007; 31 Jul 2016; tennislive.co.uk, 30 Sep 2007)CALL TO NEXT GENERATIONAfter winning the singles title at the TATP Pattaya Open in September 2017, he called for Thailand\'s younger players to be more determined to succeed in the sport. "I\'m happy to still be able to win a singles title at this age. But at the same time I\'m disappointed that the young guys still can\'t beat me. I want to tell the young players to be more determined and work harder if they want to play professional tennis. If they still can\'t beat me, it doesn\'t look good for Thai tennis." (nationmultimedia.com, 11 Sep 2017)FIRE ESCAPEIn 2008, prior to the Challenger Series tournament in Bordeaux, France, he and his twin brother Sanchai were forced to flee from their hotel because of a fire. As they were trying to escape through the smoke, they heard the voice of Yannina Ker, wife of Argentinian tennis player Lucas Arnold Ker, who was still in the building with her young son. The twins wrapped their heads with wet towels and gave towels to Yannina and her son, before helping lead them to safety. "It was a scary situation. There were no escape routes posted on the door, electrical wires were dangling from the ceiling, there was no emergency lighting in the hallway and we could barely see anything because of the smoke." (sports.espn.go.com, 13 May 2008) '), ('Hero', 'US tennis players Bob Bryan and Mike Bryan, Thai tennis player Paradorn Srichaphan. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'His father. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Relatives', 'His twin brother Sanchai also plays tennis professionally. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; sportstarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)'), ('Nickname', 'Ton (manager.co.th, 11 Jun. 2014)'), ('Education', 'Law - Sripatum University, Bangkok, THA'), ('Languages', 'English, Thai'), ('Hobbies', 'Reading, surfing the internet. (issf-sports.org, 24 Apr 2018)In 2017 he was given an Excellence Award at the Yokohama Sports Citation in Japan. (hamaspo.com, 19 Mar 2018)In 2011 he received the Totsuka-ku Citizen Honorary Award in Japan. (city.yokohama.jp, 21 Dec 2015) In 2010 he was given an Excellence Award at the annual Japanese Olympic Committee [JOC] Awards Ceremony. (sponichi.co.jp , 26 Apr 2011) In 2010 he received Big Sports Award at the TV Asahi Big Sports Award Ceremony in Japan. (tv-asahi.co.jp, 31 Dec 2010)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralGOLD IN ADVERSITYHe was in Ishinomaki, Japan, to compete in the national championships when the 2011 earthquake and tsunami struck the Pacific coast of the country. The hotel the shooters were staying in was destroyed and he considered withdrawing from the World Cup event in Sydney, NSW, Australia, later that month so he could be a part of the rescue team. However, he was encouraged to compete by his superiors at work in order to try and provide some good news for the country. He won two gold medals at the event and dedicated his success to the victims of the earthquake and tsunami. (pulse72plus.com, 28 Jul 2012; bbc.co.uk, 11 Apr 2012; sankei.jp.msn.com, 03 Mar 2012)TURNING POINTHe won a bronze medal at the 2005 Asian Championships in Bangkok, Thailand, in only his second international competition. He believes it was an important moment in his shooting career. "At that time I realised I could do it. It would not have been possible to progress further without that experience." name: KYUNSUB
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began riding horses in his sixth year of primary school. (zum.com, 24 May 2013)'), ('Reason', 'He was encouraged to take up the sport by his grandfather, who was a former horse rider. (zum.com, 24 May 2013)'), ('Awards', 'He was named the 2012 Rider of the Year by the Korea Equestrian Federation. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 18 Dec 2012) In 2011 he received an Excellence Award at the Forum of Horse Riders in the Republic of Korea. (yonhapnews.co.kr, 12 Dec 2011)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralUNCLE\'S DEATHHis uncle Kim Hyung-Chil represented the Republic of Korea in equestrian and taught him how to ride. The pair were close and Kyun-Sub was deeply affected when his uncle died after being thrown from his horse at the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. He was unable to ride for six months, but eventually returned to the sport and won gold in team dressage at the Asian Games in 2010 and 2014. "My uncle was my teacher, and he was like my father, too. I considered retirement after his death, but I returned to the sport in order to win a gold medal for him. Everything I do on a horse I learned from him. Every time I ride I think of him." (india.com, 20 Sep 2014; e2news.com, 29 Nov 2010)FURTHER EDUCATIONHe has studied for a graduate degree in physical education at Dankook University in Yongin, Republic of Korea. (Facebook profile, 28 Jul 2018) '), ('Influence', 'His father. (incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016)'), ('Relatives', 'His grandfather Kim Cheol-Gyu represented the Republic of Korea in equestrian jumping at the 1964 Olympic Games in Tokyo, while his father Kim Sung-Chil was appointed president of the Incheon Equestrian Association in 2016. His uncle Kim Hyung-Chil was also a rider, winning silver in team eventing at the 2002 Asian Games in Busan, Republic of Korea. He died after he was thrown from his horse at the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. (SportsDeskOnline, 07 Aug 2018; incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016; news.joins.com, 28 Jul 2016; hankooki.com, 21 Oct 2010)'), ('Injuries', 'He suffered injuries to his neck and his back ahead of the 2016 National Sports Festival in the Republic of Korea, after a vehicle collided with his horse trailer. He went on to win a silver medal at the tournament, despite needing an injection in his back on the day of competition. (incheonilbo.com, 09 Oct 2016)'), ('Education', 'Physical Education - Kyungwon University, Seoul, KOR'), ('Languages', 'Korean'), ('Highlights', 'EQUESTRIAN EVENTINGRankEventYearLocationAsian Games2Eventing Team2002Busan, KOR6Eventing Individual2002Busan, KOREQUESTRIAN DRESSAGERankEventYearLocationAsian Games1Dressage Team2014Incheon, KOR1Dressage Team2010Guangzhou, CHN18Dressage Individual2014Incheon, KOR22Dressage Individual2010Guangzhou, CHNEQUESTRIAN JUMPINGRankEventYearLocationWorld Cup Chinese League4Jumping Individual2016/2017Gwacheon, KOR')]

name: SIU HONG
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began the sport at age six. (Athlete, 27 Jul 2010)'), ('Reason', 'He was inspired to take up the sport by his late father. "He was my source of inspiration. If not for him, I wouldn\'t have even learned to bowl." (ejinsight.com, 25 Nov 2015)'), ('Coach', 'Kim Eui-Young, KOR (hk.sports.appledaily.com, 10 Jan 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win gold at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (bka.mpweekly.com, 23 Dec 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the masters event at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (hongkongsport.org, 13 Apr 2015)'), ('Awards', 'He received a Hong Kong Sports Star Award in 2001, 2003, 2004, 2009, 2011, 2014 and 2015 from the Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, China. (sportstar2017.hkolympic.org, 01 Jan 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCANCER SURVIVORIn 2014, at age 29, he was diagnosed with testicular cancer, which had taken his father\'s life in 2011. After being cured through surgery and chemotherapy, he continued with his bowling career. "At first I could only bowl a score of 150, but I pressed on. I didn\'t disclose my condition to my team and coach until after the [2014] Asian Games. I didn\'t want them to worry about me and affect the morale of the team. Compared to what other people have gone through, my illness is minor. When my dad was diagnosed with cancer, he lived another three or four years. Life is so unpredictable. I really want to share my experience with children and other people; they need to know that they should treasure life." (scmp.com, 06 Dec 2015; bka.mpweekly.com, 23 Dec 2017) '), ('Hero', 'US tenpin bowler Parker Bohn III. (Athlete, 24 Nov 2006)'), ('Injuries', 'In December 2017 he was unable to compete at the Storm Cup in Seoul, Republic of Korea, due to a right hand injury. name: KRISHAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began boxing at age 10 at the Bhiwani Boxing Club in India. (ndtv.com, 22 Jul 2012; msn.com, 26 Mar 2012)'), ('Reason', '"I took up boxing because most of my friends were doing it. Basically this sport is for tough people, so I also wanted to be tough and healthy." (ndtv.com, 22 Jul 2012; expressindia.com, 26 Nov 2010)'), ('Coach', 'Santiago Nieva [national] (sportstarlive.com, 14 Apr 2018; timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 02 Sep 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To turn professional by the end of 2018. (scroll.in, 11 Apr 2018)'), ('Awards', 'He was presented with the Arjuna Award in 2012. (kanglaonline.com, 19 Aug 2012)He was named Best Boxer at the 2010 National Championships in New Delhi, India. (newkerala.com, 16 Jul 2010)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralOCCUPATIONHe joined the Haryana Police in India under a sports quota programme that allows him to train and compete internationally. (ANI Twitter profile, 19 Apr 2018)LONDON LOSSHe was eliminated from the 2012 Olympic Games in London in the preliminary round, despite initially being declared the winner. His opponent Errol Spence of the United States of America successfully appealed to the International Amateur Boxing Federation [AIBA] after claiming the referee had failed to notice Vikas committing fouls and intentionally spitting out his mouth guard. India lodged a counter appeal, which failed, and then took the case to the Court of Arbitration for Sport [CAS]. This was also unsuccessful. "There is no provision in the AIBA Technical and Competition Rules allowing for an appeal against the decision of the competition jury in relation to a protest. The decision of the competition jury is final and cannot be appealed," a statement from CAS said. (ndtv.com, 06 Aug 2012, 04 Aug 2012; dnaindia.com, 04 Aug 2012)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Indian boxer to claim three medals at the Asian Games when he claimed bronze in the 75kg division at the 2018 edition in Indonesia. (india.com, 31 Aug 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 01 Sep 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Indian boxers Jai Bhagwan, Vijender Singh and Jagdish Singh. (thehindu.com, 02 Jun 2010; indianexpress.com, 20 May 2010)'), ('Injuries', 'A cut eyelid forced him to withdraw from his semifinal bout at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (thehindu.com, 29 Aug 2018; india.com, 31 Aug 2018)He suffered a hand injury in 2017. (timesofindia.indiatimes.com, 01 Apr 2018)An eye injury meant he was unable to compete at the selection event for the India team in Patiala ahead of the 2014 Commonwealth Games. (intoday.in, 24 May 2014)He competed at the 2011 World Championships in Baku, Azerbaijan, with a injured wrist. He won a bronze medal at the event. (livemint.com, 20 Jan 2012)In 2011 he was unable to compete in the final of London Prepares, which was the test event for the 2012 Olympic Games. He had injured his left wrist in the semifinal of the event. (ndtv.com, 28 Nov 2011)'), ('Education', 'Kurukshetra University, India'), ('Languages', 'English, Hindi'), ('Hobbies', 'Running, football, music. (city.mitoyo.lg.jp, 07 Jul 2014)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHe became the first Japanese athlete to win a men's singles world championship medal when he claimed bronze at the 2015 World Championships in Jakarta, Indonesia. In 2015 he also became the first Japanese player to win a men's singles Super Series Final when he claimed gold at the tournament in Dubai, United Arab Emirates. (Reuters.com, 04 Dec 2017; hochi.co.jp, 02 Jun 2018; euronews.com, 08 Apr 2016)SUSPENSIONIn April 2016 he was suspended from the Japanese national team by the Nippon Badminton Association after admitting to gambling in an illegal casino in Japan. The suspension ruled him out of contention for the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. He was allowed to return to lower-level international tournaments in mid-2017, and the suspension was wholly lifted in January 2018. (Reuters.com, 04 Dec 2017; japantimes.co.jp, 12 Mar 2017; euronews.com, 08 Apr 2016) "), ('Injuries', 'In January 2018 he sprained his left ankle and required three weeks of recovery. bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up athletics in 2005, beginning in long jump and triple jump before switching to high jump in 2006. (esyria.sy, 11 Aug 2011)'), ('Reason', 'His father encouraged him to get involved in the sport after seeing how tall he was becoming. (esyria.sy, 11 Aug 2011)'), ('Debut', '2007 for Syrian Arab Republic, in Jordan (iaaf.org, 25 Feb 2010)'), ('Coach', 'Imad Siraj [personal] (esyria.sy, 26 Aug 2017)'), ('Awards', 'He was flag bearer for the Syrian Arab Republic at the opening ceremony of the Olympic Games in 2012 and 2016. (iaaf.org, 09 Oct 2017; dailystar.com.lb, 19 May 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSPORTING DIFFICULTIESHe lives in Damascus, Syrian Arab Republic, and has experienced problems in obtaining visas since the conflict began there in 2011. He was unable to participate in the 2017 Diamond League meeting in Rabat, Morocco, after he was refused the necessary papers to enter the country, although he later managed to acquire a six-month visa that allowed him to compete in Europe through a Spanish embassy. He also has to go to Beirut, Lebanon, in order to travel to his events as there are no international flights to and from the Syrian Arab Republic. "I\'m an expert in embassies, where they are, their addresses, when they open, when they close, what documents you need for a visa. I\'m an administrative expert in this subject. Everyone is surprised when I say I still train and live in Syria, especially as I am among the top six in the world." (sport360.com, 09 Aug 2017)OCCUPATIONHe works for the Ministry of Education in the Syrian Arab Republic. (Facebook profile, 21 Apr 2018) '), ('Nickname', 'Jojo Jump (Facebook profile, 21 Apr 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'He was forced to battle a severe case of anaemia while competing at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. bio: [('Beginning', 'He began playing table tennis at age seven under the guidance of his father, who also played the sport competitively. (ultimatetabletennis.in, 23 Aug 2017; livemint.com, 01 Feb 2012; thefangarage.com, 15 Jul 2017)'), ('Reason', '"I picked it up looking at my father, who was a table tennis player. He was my childhood coach and I owe a huge part of my success to the training given by him." (ultimatetabletennis.in, 23 Aug 2017; thehindu.com, 06 Sep 2014)'), ('Coach', 'N Ravichandran [national], IND (redbull.com, 20 Jul 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To break into the world top 100 rankings. (rediff.com, 07 Sep 2017)'), ('Awards', "In August 2017 he received the Arjuna Award from the Indian government's Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports in recognition of his sporting achievements. The Arjuna Award is the highest sporting award in India. (ultimatetabletennis.in, 23 Aug 2017)In 2012 he was named Sportsperson of the Year by the Calcutta Sports Journalists' Club [CSJC]. (cricketcountry.com, 19 Apr 2012)"), ('Additional Information', "Style of playAttack (ultimatetabletennis.in, 01 Jul 2017)GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTIn April 2017 paired with Soumyajit Ghosh they became the first Indian men's doubles pair to win a title on either the ITTF Challenge Series or ITTF World Tour. They marked the achievement at the 2017 Challenge Chile Open in Santiago, Chile. (ittf.com, 30 Apr 2017)OCCUPATIONHe joined the Oil and Natural Gas Corporation of India under a sports quota programme that allows him to train and compete internationally. (sportstarlive.com, 02 Aug 2017)FAMILY TABLE TENNIS ACADEMYHis father, Arputharaj Anthony, runs the Amala Annai Table Tennis Academy for underprivileged children in Chennai, India. name: SATHIYAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began the sport at age five at a neighbourhood table tennis academy in Chennai, India, where a coach noticed his talent and encouraged him to enrol in the academy. At age seven he started competing at state level, and by age 12 he was competing at national level. (educationtimes.com, 31 Jul 2017)'), ('Reason', 'He was always passionate about the sport, but did not concentrate on it full-time until after he graduated from university. "There was a point in life when I was in a dilemma. I had to make a decision between education and table tennis. Table tennis has always been my first love. I had an immense passion for it, though I had a liking for science and computers too. When I was doing both at the same time [at university], that was when I realised that I should take up the sport as my profession, as that was the only thing which made me feel complete." (thefield.scroll.in, 23 Jul 2017; sportskeeda.com, 05 Sep 2017)'), ('Coach', 'N Ravichandran [club], IND; Massimo Costantini [national], ITA; Subramaniam Raman [personal], IND, from 2013 (ittf.com, 06 Jan 2018, 12 Jun 2017, 03 Sep 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a team medal at the Olympic Games. (newsclick.in, 25 Apr 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning the men's singles title at the 2016 Belgium Open. (sportskeeda.com, 31 May 2017)"), ('Additional Information', 'GripShakehand (ultimatetabletennis.in, 01 Jul 2017)Style of playAttack (ultimatetabletennis.in, 01 Jul 2017)GeneralBALANCING SPORT AND STUDYHe grew up in a family where the traditional focus was on education rather than sport. He says it was difficult balancing his university degree in engineering with his training, and he would often compete at tournaments on just a few hours sleep due to his study commitments. After he graduated in 2014, he decided to dedicate himself to table tennis full-time. "The only reason I completed my engineering degree was because I wanted to get it out of the way. My dream is and always will be to be the world\'s best table tennis player, but every athlete who wants to represent their country needs to make sacrifices. This was mine, I needed to prove to my family that I\'m strong enough to do both." (ittf.com, 26 Sep 2016; thefield.scroll.in, 23 Jul 2017; sportskeeda.com, 05 Sep 2017)OCCUPATIONHe works as a human resources executive for the Oil and Natural Gas Corporation of India [ONGC], as part of a sports quota programme that allows him to train and compete internationally. (Facebook page, 04 Nov 2017; Facebook profile, 15 Oct 2017) '), ('Influence', 'Indian table tennis player Sharath Kamal Achanta. name: HARMEET RAJUL
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began playing the sport at age six with his older brother, under the guidance of their father, who was their first coach. "I was six years old, my father played table tennis at his university. He bought a table tennis board home. I loved to play on that when I was little, I always wanted to play." (idrottonline.se, 10 Dec 2013)'), ('Reason', 'The influence of his father and older brother drove him to compete at the highest level. "It was love at first site with table tennis for me. I couldn\'t imagine my life without it. It was my decision at the age of 6-7 to take it up seriously. My parents also have a really big role to play in where I am today. They always supported me and encouraged me to follow my heart. The game has helped me in more ways than one. It has given me the opportunity to make my country proud, it has helped me to be a better human being, and I have travelled to more than 40 countries to represent India." (idrottonline.se, 2013; We Love Surat Youtube Channel, 23 Jul 2016; thesportsrush.com, 15 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Peter Karlsson [personal], SWE; Hraday Desai [brother], IND (ittf.com, 04 May 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the Commonwealth Games and Asian Games. name: Alex
bio: [('Beginning', "He began riding in 1994 at the Beijing Equestrian Club in the People's Republic of China. (mingren.maigoo.com, 2016)"), ('Reason', 'He grew up surrounded by horses, so riding came naturally to him. (rideaway.co.uk, 10 Jun 2015)'), ('Debut', '2005 for China, in France (sports.sina.com.cn, 09 Mar 2016)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the individual event at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (sohu.com, 24 Oct 2014)'), ('Awards', 'In 2016 he was presented with the China News Week Award for Most Influential Sports Person of the Year. (everythinghorseuk.co.uk, 29 Dec 2016)In 2010 he was given the Rising Star award by the International Equestrian Federation [FEI]. (qq.com, 24 Mar 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFIRSTSAt the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing, he became the first Chinese rider to compete in an Olympic equestrian event. At the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, he became the first Chinese equestrian to win an individual medal at the Games by claiming silver in the eventing competition. (horseandhound.co.uk, 31 Oct 2015; sohu.com, 24 Oct 2014; 163.com, 12 Nov 2010; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018)STABLESTogether with his partner Sarah Higgins, he runs Pinfold Stables in Knutsford, England. (thegaitpost.com, 28 May 2017; dailymail.co.uk, 24 Aug 2016)OTHER ACTIVITIESHe has worked as an ambassador for the Red Cross, and also supports a charity called \'Horsemanship\' in the People\'s Republic of China. "The charity is all about changing perceptions and connecting communities with equestrianism. We run programmes with as many grassroots riding schools as possible. And we connect these riding schools with children from wealthy families but also children from local communities who cannot afford lessons."
